[Sample 1] Integrating Solana Blinks: A Developer’s Quickstart

Overview
Solana Blinks (Blockchain Links) are a 2026 standard that allows any Solana Action to be rendered as a rich, interactive interface on any platform that supports a URL (Twitter, Discord, etc.). This guide teaches developers how to turn a standard "Donate SOL" action into a shareable Blink.

1. Prerequisites
Node.js v18 or higher.

Solana CLI installed.

A basic understanding of Next.js or Express.

The @solana/actions-sdk package.

Bash
npm install @solana/actions-sdk @solana/web3.js
2. Setting up the Action API
A Blink starts with a standard API that follows the Solana Actions specification. You need two main endpoints: GET (to describe the action) and POST (to execute the transaction).

The GET Response
This tells the "Blink client" (like a Twitter browser extension) what to display to the user.

The Script usually:
// pages/api/donate/get.ts
export const GET = async (req: Request) => {
  const payload = {
    icon: "https://your-dapp.com/donate-icon.png",
    title: "Support the Creator",
    description: "Donate 0.1 SOL to support this project's development.",
    label: "Donate 0.1 SOL",
  };

  return Response.json(payload, {
    headers: { 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin': '*' } // Critical for Blinks
  });
};
3. Handling the POST Transaction
When the user clicks the "Donate" button on the Blink, the client sends a POST request to your server. Your server then creates a transaction for the user to sign.

The Script usually:
// pages/api/donate/post.ts
import { Transaction, SystemProgram, PublicKey } from "@solana/web3.js";

export const POST = async (req: Request) => {
  const { account } = await req.json(); // The user's wallet address
  
  const transaction = new Transaction().add(
    SystemProgram.transfer({
      fromPubkey: new PublicKey(account),
      toPubkey: new PublicKey("YOUR_RECEIVE_WALLET_ADDRESS"),
      lamports: 100000000, // 0.1 SOL
    })
  );

  // Set the latest blockhash
  transaction.recentBlockhash = (await connection.getLatestBlockhash()).blockhash;
  transaction.feePayer = new PublicKey(account);

  const payload = {
    transaction: transaction.serialize({ requireAllSignatures: false }).toString("base64"),
    message: "Thank you for your donation!",
  };

  return Response.json(payload);
};
4. Testing Your Blink
To see your Blink in action before deploying:

Use the Solana Blinks Inspector tool.

Paste your local API URL (e.g., http://localhost:3000/api/donate).

Ensure your CORS headers are set to *, otherwise, the client will block the request.

Why this sample works for your portfolio:
It’s Current: It uses the 2026 Actions SDK.

It’s Practical: Every project wants a "Donate" or "Buy" button they can share on social media.

It’s Clean: It uses TypeScript and follows the official Solana style guide.
